Boil a full #kettle{}. Put the @couscous{120%g} into a large #bowl{}.

Pour in the boiling @water for the couscous{240%ml}, stir in the @chicken stock paste{10%g}, then cover tightly with #cling film{}.

Leave to the side for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, trim the @courgette{1} and slice into 1cm thick rounds.

Heat a large #frying pan{} on high heat (no oil).

When hot, add the courgette and cook until charred, ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn only every couple of minutes - this will result in the courgette picking up some nice colour.

Once cooked, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then transfer to a bowl.

While the courgette is cooking, pop another large frying pan on medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{260%g} to the pan and season with salt and pepper.

Cook until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Add the @chermoula spice mix{1} and @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g} to the chicken. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Pour the @water for the sauce{75%ml} into the pan.

Bring to the boil then lower the heat and simmer gently.

Simmer until the chicken is cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes}, stirring occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @dill{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Combine the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g} and half the dill in a small bowl.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, stir together then set aside.

Fluff up the couscous with a #fork{}, stir through the charred courgette and remaining dill.

Once the chicken is cooked, stir the @red pepper chilli jelly{25%g} into the pan then remove from the heat. Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed.

Share the couscous between your bowls and spoon the glazed chicken on top, making sure you get all the sauce from the pan.

Finish with a dollop of dill yoghurt.

Enjoy!